1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,420
 (soft music)

2
00:00:02,420 --> 00:00:15,900
 - Thank you very much for Dr. Wright's illuminating lecture.

3
00:00:15,900 --> 00:00:18,260
 It rightly reminds us that Christian ethics

4
00:00:18,260 --> 00:00:19,980
 is more than a set of do's and don'ts.

5
00:00:19,980 --> 00:00:24,260
 It is indivisible from our identity and our purpose.

6
00:00:24,260 --> 00:00:25,740
 Now it's time for respondents.

7
00:00:25,740 --> 00:00:29,620
 Dr. Edwin Moon, lecturer in Old Testament

8
00:00:29,620 --> 00:00:31,500
 from Chinese Mission Seminary,

9
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:33,620
 will be the first respondent.

10
00:00:33,620 --> 00:00:35,620
 After that, Dr. Chun-Lun Wu,

11
00:00:35,620 --> 00:00:39,100
 assistant professor in Biblical Studies from CJSC,

12
00:00:39,100 --> 00:00:41,020
 will carry the conversation on.

13
00:00:41,020 --> 00:00:42,220
 So Dr. Moon, please.

14
00:00:42,220 --> 00:00:49,540
 (audience applauding)

15
00:00:49,540 --> 00:00:56,140
 - Thank you, Dr. Wright,

16
00:00:56,140 --> 00:00:59,360
 for coming over to Hong Kong to present us.

17
00:00:59,360 --> 00:01:04,360
 With a series of stimulating and insightful lectures.

18
00:01:04,360 --> 00:01:10,340
 And thank you, President Wong and CJST

19
00:01:10,340 --> 00:01:11,660
 for inviting me to respond

20
00:01:11,660 --> 00:01:13,940
 to Dr. Wright's lecture this afternoon.

21
00:01:13,940 --> 00:01:20,020
 Dr. Wright is one of the pioneers on Christian ethics

22
00:01:20,020 --> 00:01:24,940
 and a prolific writer on this subject matter,

23
00:01:24,940 --> 00:01:27,360
 especially in the field of the Old Testament.

24
00:01:28,660 --> 00:01:30,180
 Many of us are familiar with

25
00:01:30,180 --> 00:01:34,020
 Dr. Wright's paradigmatic approach

26
00:01:34,020 --> 00:01:38,780
 that links God, humanity, and the earth in a triangle

27
00:01:38,780 --> 00:01:44,340
 and integrates Israel in the Old Testament

28
00:01:44,340 --> 00:01:48,100
 and the church in the New Testament in a subtriangle,

29
00:01:48,100 --> 00:01:52,640
 both typologically and eschatologically.

30
00:01:52,640 --> 00:01:56,340
 I would like to acknowledge Dr. Wright's lecture

31
00:01:56,340 --> 00:01:58,160
 in the following three aspects.

32
00:01:59,180 --> 00:02:04,180
 First of all, I appreciate Dr. Wright's holistic

33
00:02:04,180 --> 00:02:09,720
 and eschatological approach in cultivating the topic,

34
00:02:09,720 --> 00:02:12,540
 the Old Testament and Christian ethics.

35
00:02:12,540 --> 00:02:13,760
 How should we live?

36
00:02:13,760 --> 00:02:18,860
 Dr. Wright clearly demonstrates the Pentateuch

37
00:02:18,860 --> 00:02:22,280
 as a paradigm and the revelation of God

38
00:02:22,280 --> 00:02:23,580
 for Christian ethics.

39
00:02:24,720 --> 00:02:29,720
 Dr. Wright thoughtfully selects four representative passages

40
00:02:29,720 --> 00:02:34,800
 from each book of the Pentateuch, except numbers.

41
00:02:34,800 --> 00:02:38,840
 I wholly agree with Dr. Wright's missional

42
00:02:38,840 --> 00:02:43,480
 and ethical hermeneutics of the election of Abraham

43
00:02:43,480 --> 00:02:46,820
 in Genesis chapter 18, verse 18 and 19.

44
00:02:46,820 --> 00:02:50,320
 The incision of the two purple crosses

45
00:02:51,200 --> 00:02:56,200
 for the purpose that is judicious and makes God's purpose

46
00:02:56,200 --> 00:02:59,140
 of the election crystal clear.

47
00:02:59,140 --> 00:03:05,560
 This missional election corresponds and further elaborates

48
00:03:05,560 --> 00:03:10,720
 the Abrahamic covenant in Genesis chapter 12, verse 1 to 3.

49
00:03:10,720 --> 00:03:15,660
 Abraham and his descendants are chosen

50
00:03:15,660 --> 00:03:19,680
 for the ethical mission to walk in the way of the Lord

51
00:03:19,680 --> 00:03:22,060
 and to do justice and righteousness.

52
00:03:22,060 --> 00:03:28,140
 Indeed, that is God's mission of blessing all nations

53
00:03:28,140 --> 00:03:31,020
 through the chosen family of Abraham.

54
00:03:31,020 --> 00:03:37,200
 Dr. Wright tactfully connects the identity of Israel

55
00:03:37,200 --> 00:03:43,160
 as the descendants of Abraham with the missional redemption

56
00:03:43,160 --> 00:03:47,460
 of the nation of Israel in Exodus.

57
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:52,400
 The arguments for the missional ethics

58
00:03:52,400 --> 00:03:54,600
 and the covenantal community of Israel

59
00:03:54,600 --> 00:04:00,600
 in the programmatic text of Exodus chapter 19,

60
00:04:00,600 --> 00:04:05,840
 verse 4 through 6, Leviticus 19 and Deuteronomy chapter 4,

61
00:04:05,840 --> 00:04:12,440
 6 to 8 are convincingly knitted together

62
00:04:12,440 --> 00:04:14,620
 and evidently presented.

63
00:04:15,920 --> 00:04:20,920
 Secondly, Dr. Wright introduced a concrete example

64
00:04:20,920 --> 00:04:25,960
 of an unethical corrupted city of Sodom

65
00:04:25,960 --> 00:04:31,020
 that depicts the fallenness of our world today.

66
00:04:31,020 --> 00:04:37,440
 It urges Christians to reflect on the reality

67
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:42,520
 of judgment and salvation

68
00:04:42,520 --> 00:04:45,840
 in the light of our missional ethical calling

69
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:48,120
 to walk in the way of the Lord

70
00:04:48,120 --> 00:04:50,680
 and do justice and righteousness.

71
00:04:50,680 --> 00:04:54,920
 Dr. Wright translates the abstract ethical principle

72
00:04:54,920 --> 00:05:00,760
 of Leviticus 19 into down-to-earth pragmatic advice.

73
00:05:00,760 --> 00:05:09,520
 These ethical codes of living in Leviticus 19

74
00:05:09,520 --> 00:05:12,540
 are both relevant and practical

75
00:05:12,540 --> 00:05:14,280
 for the Christian community today.

76
00:05:15,680 --> 00:05:18,880
 They reflect the holiness of God,

77
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:23,320
 and we as Christians are called to separate from this world

78
00:05:23,320 --> 00:05:26,720
 and walk in the way of the Lord

79
00:05:26,720 --> 00:05:29,480
 to do righteousness and justice.

80
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:35,640
 The list is a microcosm of ethical living

81
00:05:35,640 --> 00:05:40,140
 that incorporates in all capacity of living,

82
00:05:40,140 --> 00:05:45,140
 namely social, economic, legal,

83
00:05:45,840 --> 00:05:50,180
 political, and religious dimensions of our society.

84
00:05:50,180 --> 00:05:54,600
 We are being challenged to transform

85
00:05:54,600 --> 00:05:59,000
 these holiness living codes into practice

86
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:02,360
 in our existing social institutions and structures.

87
00:06:02,360 --> 00:06:06,120
 We are reminded to be a community of faith

88
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:10,920
 to fulfill God's mission to bless all nations.

89
00:06:13,480 --> 00:06:17,880
 Last but not least, Dr. Wright beautifully conclude

90
00:06:17,880 --> 00:06:22,280
 his presentation with Paul and Peter's teachings,

91
00:06:22,280 --> 00:06:24,920
 which are written in the Old Testament.

92
00:06:24,920 --> 00:06:27,880
 It demonstrates that there's continuity

93
00:06:27,880 --> 00:06:31,600
 between the Old Testament and the New Testament.

94
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:36,120
 Dr. Wright further quotes the Cape Town Commitment

95
00:06:36,120 --> 00:06:39,640
 of the Lausanne Movement to summarize his conclusion

96
00:06:39,640 --> 00:06:44,640
 that we share the same missional identity

97
00:06:44,640 --> 00:06:48,760
 and missional purpose to live out the missional ethics

98
00:06:48,760 --> 00:06:52,480
 of Abraham and the people of Israel.

99
00:06:52,480 --> 00:06:54,280
 We are God's chosen people.

100
00:06:54,280 --> 00:07:00,000
 Through the redemption and resurrection of Jesus Christ,

101
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:03,040
 we all partake in God's mission

102
00:07:03,040 --> 00:07:06,460
 to bless all nations through evangelism.

103
00:07:08,200 --> 00:07:10,480
 As a teacher of the Old Testament,

104
00:07:10,480 --> 00:07:13,920
 I share Dr. Wright's concern of the lack of understanding

105
00:07:13,920 --> 00:07:16,600
 of the Old Testament in the Christian community.

106
00:07:16,600 --> 00:07:20,800
 I agree with Dr. Wright that if we do not know

107
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:25,800
 the drama of the scripture, both the Old and New Testaments,

108
00:07:25,800 --> 00:07:30,160
 we may lose our grip on our identity,

109
00:07:30,160 --> 00:07:34,000
 our purpose of existence, and fail to live

110
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:37,200
 according to God's attributes and mission.

111
00:07:38,480 --> 00:07:43,480
 In closing, I would like to respond to Dr. Wright's

112
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:48,680
 final paragraph on obeying God's laws.

113
00:07:48,680 --> 00:07:55,440
 Sometimes, even though we are familiar with the plots

114
00:07:55,440 --> 00:08:00,480
 and the story of the scripture, remember commandments,

115
00:08:00,480 --> 00:08:03,760
 and know God's attributes and mission,

116
00:08:03,760 --> 00:08:05,760
 we may still have difficulties.

117
00:08:06,760 --> 00:08:11,400
 We can struggle to figure out how should we live ethically,

118
00:08:11,400 --> 00:08:15,160
 according to the scripture, in a sophisticated,

119
00:08:15,160 --> 00:08:19,360
 post-modern commercial world that is dominated

120
00:08:19,360 --> 00:08:25,240
 by materialism, consumerism, relativism, and self-centeredness.

121
00:08:25,240 --> 00:08:34,120
 How do we obey God's law in such controversial gray areas,

122
00:08:34,480 --> 00:08:38,600
 especially in the arena of social justice,

123
00:08:38,600 --> 00:08:43,720
 under the rule of atheist governments

124
00:08:43,720 --> 00:08:46,920
 or anti-Christianity authorities,

125
00:08:46,920 --> 00:08:53,680
 when everyone is doing what is just in his or her own eyes?

126
00:08:53,680 --> 00:08:56,400
 What is our stance?

127
00:08:56,400 --> 00:09:01,200
 The programmatic texts in Deuteronomy chapter four,

128
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:06,200
 verse six through eight, also Deuteronomy chapter 10,

129
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:09,160
 verse 12 through 19,

130
00:09:09,160 --> 00:09:15,040
 both shed light in response to the questions about.

131
00:09:15,040 --> 00:09:20,880
 It says, "For observing the law will show wisdom

132
00:09:20,880 --> 00:09:23,520
 "and understanding to the nation.

133
00:09:23,520 --> 00:09:27,760
 "Surely, this great nation is wise and understanding people.

134
00:09:28,640 --> 00:09:32,800
 "Wisdom and understanding will equip us

135
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:35,000
 "to obey God's law

136
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,080
 "and live out our missional and ethical calling."

137
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:42,880
 The wisdom literature in the Old Testament,

138
00:09:42,880 --> 00:09:46,480
 namely the book of Proverbs, the book of Job,

139
00:09:46,480 --> 00:09:48,600
 and the book of Ecclesiastes,

140
00:09:48,600 --> 00:09:52,720
 summarize wisdom in one phrase, fear of the Lord.

141
00:09:52,720 --> 00:09:57,760
 If we fear the Lord, we'll keep his commandments

142
00:09:57,760 --> 00:10:02,760
 as concluded in Ecclesiastes chapter 12, verse 13,

143
00:10:02,760 --> 00:10:05,880
 and we'll turn away from evil,

144
00:10:05,880 --> 00:10:10,000
 as stated in Job chapter one, verse one and eight,

145
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:11,360
 chapter two, verse three,

146
00:10:11,360 --> 00:10:15,640
 and chapter 28, verse 28.

147
00:10:15,640 --> 00:10:21,120
 It will lead us to walk with the Lord

148
00:10:21,120 --> 00:10:22,840
 and follow his instructions.

149
00:10:22,840 --> 00:10:25,600
 The fear of the Lord is concerned

150
00:10:25,600 --> 00:10:27,960
 with the knowledge of the Lord

151
00:10:27,960 --> 00:10:29,840
 in Proverbs chapter nine, verse 10.

152
00:10:29,840 --> 00:10:32,920
 The knowledge of the Lord is not only limited

153
00:10:32,920 --> 00:10:34,080
 to head knowledge.

154
00:10:34,080 --> 00:10:41,360
 Memorizing the golden verses of the scripture

155
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:44,680
 in Chinese Christian traditions,

156
00:10:44,680 --> 00:10:47,920
 but also on focusing on our relationship with the Lord.

157
00:10:47,920 --> 00:10:52,960
 As the psalmist echoes Moses' teaching

158
00:10:52,960 --> 00:10:55,800
 in Deuteronomy chapter four, verse seven,

159
00:10:55,800 --> 00:10:58,920
 the Lord is dear to all who call on him.

160
00:10:58,920 --> 00:11:03,920
 Psalm 145, 18a.

161
00:11:03,920 --> 00:11:12,600
 A close relationship with God and calling on him

162
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:16,480
 when we are lost will help us to discern God's will

163
00:11:16,480 --> 00:11:19,920
 and guide us to make wise decision

164
00:11:19,920 --> 00:11:22,080
 to live out our missional witness.

165
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:26,280
 And I found out that Dr. Wright mentioned

166
00:11:26,280 --> 00:11:28,920
 about Isaiah chapter 58.

167
00:11:28,920 --> 00:11:33,960
 And I think that's not in the script.

168
00:11:33,960 --> 00:11:39,160
 And then it triggered me to think about this chapter,

169
00:11:39,160 --> 00:11:42,120
 because I remember there's a very

170
00:11:42,120 --> 00:11:47,480
 interesting proclaimed by the Lord.

171
00:11:47,480 --> 00:11:51,560
 We are family with Isaiah chapter six,

172
00:11:51,560 --> 00:11:54,720
 when God asked, "Who can I send?"

173
00:11:54,720 --> 00:12:00,600
 Then Isaiah responds, "Here I am."

174
00:12:00,600 --> 00:12:03,160
 But in Isaiah chapter 58,

175
00:12:03,160 --> 00:12:06,520
 when we refrain from oppression,

176
00:12:06,520 --> 00:12:10,640
 when we are practicing justice,

177
00:12:10,640 --> 00:12:14,840
 then God will answer, "Here I am."

178
00:12:14,840 --> 00:12:17,400
 I think it's in chapter 58, verse nine,

179
00:12:17,400 --> 00:12:18,600
 or something like that.

180
00:12:19,520 --> 00:12:24,120
 Okay, the Chinese translation of the title

181
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:26,800
 of today's lecture is quite interesting

182
00:12:26,800 --> 00:12:28,640
 and thought-provoking.

183
00:12:28,640 --> 00:12:31,320
 Instead of a literal translation of the question,

184
00:12:31,320 --> 00:12:33,280
 "How should we live?"

185
00:12:33,280 --> 00:12:38,280
 It is translated as a statement in English,

186
00:12:38,280 --> 00:12:43,640
 "Obey and follow this," or "Obey and do this."

187
00:12:43,640 --> 00:12:47,440
 In Chinese, the title is "Zhen Qi Yi Hao."

188
00:12:48,520 --> 00:12:53,000
 It connotes a sense of doing rather than being or relating.

189
00:12:53,000 --> 00:13:01,560
 Indeed, living our missional ethical living

190
00:13:01,560 --> 00:13:03,080
 is a matter of doing.

191
00:13:03,080 --> 00:13:07,360
 The underlying force of doing this or that,

192
00:13:07,360 --> 00:13:12,360
 in addition to the understanding of our identity and mission,

193
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:14,560
 is to trust and obey.

194
00:13:17,160 --> 00:13:20,160
 The Book of Numbers reveals stories

195
00:13:20,160 --> 00:13:23,560
 of the Israelites' failure to trust and obey

196
00:13:23,560 --> 00:13:25,600
 during their wandering in the wilderness.

197
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:30,520
 God pronounced that Israel has tested

198
00:13:30,520 --> 00:13:35,520
 and disobeyed him 10 times in Numbers chapter 14, verse 22.

199
00:13:35,520 --> 00:13:40,720
 The renowned story of Joshua and Caleb,

200
00:13:40,720 --> 00:13:43,240
 two trustful and obedient spies,

201
00:13:43,240 --> 00:13:47,800
 were being accused by 10 doubtful, fearful,

202
00:13:47,800 --> 00:13:50,960
 and disobedient spies.

203
00:13:50,960 --> 00:13:55,880
 The latter's fear and doubt influenced the Israelites.

204
00:13:55,880 --> 00:13:58,640
 Fear and doubt are stumbling blocks

205
00:13:58,640 --> 00:14:01,160
 in our way to obey the Lord

206
00:14:01,160 --> 00:14:05,320
 and carrying out our ethical mission.

207
00:14:05,320 --> 00:14:09,320
 Due to distrust, Moses lost his destiny

208
00:14:09,320 --> 00:14:13,040
 of leading Israel to the Promised Land,

209
00:14:13,040 --> 00:14:16,440
 as found in Numbers chapter 20, verse 12.

210
00:14:16,440 --> 00:14:23,160
 I think love God is the root of obeying his law.

211
00:14:23,160 --> 00:14:29,640
 Jesus mentioned three times about loving him

212
00:14:29,640 --> 00:14:32,320
 and obeying his commandments.

213
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:37,320
 In John chapter 14, verse 15, 21, 23.

214
00:14:37,320 --> 00:14:41,680
 Love and obey go hand in hand.

215
00:14:41,680 --> 00:14:45,160
 Love drives away fear and doubt,

216
00:14:45,160 --> 00:14:48,440
 the stumbling blocks of trusting and obeying God's law.

217
00:14:48,440 --> 00:14:53,040
 Our Lord Jesus Christ is an excellent example

218
00:14:53,040 --> 00:14:55,160
 of obeying our Heavenly Father.

219
00:14:55,160 --> 00:15:00,120
 In his prayer in Gethsemane,

220
00:15:00,120 --> 00:15:03,600
 he seeks God's will over his own will.

221
00:15:03,600 --> 00:15:08,040
 May we be found faithful and loving

222
00:15:08,040 --> 00:15:10,920
 in carrying out our missional ethics

223
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:15,360
 and love God with all our heart and with all our soul

224
00:15:15,360 --> 00:15:19,480
 and with all our strength and with all our mind

225
00:15:19,480 --> 00:15:22,640
 and love our neighbor as ourselves.

226
00:15:22,640 --> 00:15:25,880
 For love is the fulfillment of the law.

227
00:15:25,880 --> 00:15:30,320
 May we adhere to obey God's missional ethics,

228
00:15:30,320 --> 00:15:33,000
 despite how great the causes are.

229
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:38,400
 Once again, I would like to extend my sincere gratitude

230
00:15:38,400 --> 00:15:43,400
 to Dr. Wright for your marvelous and inspiring lecture.

231
00:15:43,400 --> 00:15:46,400
 Thank you.

232
00:15:46,400 --> 00:15:49,560
 (audience applauding)

233
00:15:49,560 --> 00:16:05,720
 - It is indeed my great privilege to have the opportunity

234
00:16:05,720 --> 00:16:07,840
 to respond to one of the lectures.

235
00:16:07,840 --> 00:16:09,040
 Delivered by Dr. Wright

236
00:16:09,040 --> 00:16:11,280
 in the Josephine Soh Lecture Week this year.

237
00:16:11,280 --> 00:16:14,440
 As suggested by the title written for us,

238
00:16:14,440 --> 00:16:16,840
 "The Old Testament as Christian Scripture."

239
00:16:16,840 --> 00:16:18,400
 The base of 10 of the lecture series

240
00:16:18,400 --> 00:16:21,520
 is the relevancy of the Old Testament for us,

241
00:16:21,520 --> 00:16:23,800
 a community of faith today as scripture.

242
00:16:23,800 --> 00:16:26,240
 Building upon his first lecture

243
00:16:26,240 --> 00:16:28,400
 on the Old Testament and Christian identity

244
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:29,280
 and second lecture

245
00:16:29,280 --> 00:16:31,480
 on the Old Testament and Christian mission,

246
00:16:31,480 --> 00:16:34,520
 Dr. Wright brought our thoughts and focus this afternoon

247
00:16:34,520 --> 00:16:37,280
 to the subject of the Old Testament and Christian ethics,

248
00:16:37,280 --> 00:16:39,160
 which addresses the question

249
00:16:39,160 --> 00:16:41,680
 of how we should live as Christians

250
00:16:41,680 --> 00:16:43,320
 in our contemporary society.

251
00:16:43,320 --> 00:16:46,800
 The lectures indeed come in a natural sequence

252
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:49,480
 as regards the relevancy of the Old Testament

253
00:16:49,480 --> 00:16:52,000
 in terms of implications for Christian life.

254
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:56,360
 While Christian identity is concerned about who we are,

255
00:16:56,360 --> 00:16:58,440
 as defined in the beginning,

256
00:16:58,440 --> 00:17:01,480
 and Christian mission looks to what we ultimately aim for

257
00:17:01,480 --> 00:17:02,320
 in the end,

258
00:17:03,240 --> 00:17:07,440
 Christian ethics comes to address the in-between process

259
00:17:07,440 --> 00:17:10,120
 and, if you frame it theologically,

260
00:17:10,120 --> 00:17:14,680
 the already but not yet reality that we are facing today.

261
00:17:14,680 --> 00:17:17,000
 Simply put, Christian ethics is about

262
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:19,400
 how we ought to live our present life

263
00:17:19,400 --> 00:17:22,080
 in accordance with our rooted identity

264
00:17:22,080 --> 00:17:25,280
 and our mission that we are anticipating to fulfill.

265
00:17:25,280 --> 00:17:28,600
 The way the Christian community is expected to live

266
00:17:28,600 --> 00:17:32,560
 in the world has undoubtedly been a significant

267
00:17:32,560 --> 00:17:34,360
 and indeed indispensable issue

268
00:17:34,360 --> 00:17:37,200
 to be addressed in Christian scholarship.

269
00:17:37,200 --> 00:17:40,880
 This has become even more so in the post-modern age,

270
00:17:40,880 --> 00:17:43,480
 in which systems of moral values and ethics

271
00:17:43,480 --> 00:17:44,760
 are being relativized,

272
00:17:44,760 --> 00:17:49,680
 despite a growing interest in ethics in secular scholarship.

273
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:51,720
 Over the past few decades,

274
00:17:51,720 --> 00:17:54,080
 there have not been many Christian scholars

275
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:57,320
 who are committed to investigating the biblical material

276
00:17:57,320 --> 00:17:58,920
 as regards Christian ethics.

277
00:17:58,920 --> 00:18:02,080
 The situation is shown to be more evident

278
00:18:02,080 --> 00:18:04,520
 with the subject of Old Testament ethics,

279
00:18:04,520 --> 00:18:08,400
 which finds an echo in the comment of Ronald Clemens.

280
00:18:08,400 --> 00:18:09,880
 The subject of Old Testament ethics

281
00:18:09,880 --> 00:18:12,920
 proved to be a most difficult one to deal with.

282
00:18:12,920 --> 00:18:17,200
 The literature devoted to it has been surprisingly sparse.

283
00:18:17,200 --> 00:18:21,960
 Dr. Wright is among a few who has actively been addressing

284
00:18:21,960 --> 00:18:24,480
 the ethical import of the Old Testament.

285
00:18:24,480 --> 00:18:27,720
 With the publication of his Old Testament ethics

286
00:18:27,720 --> 00:18:30,920
 for the people of God in 2004,

287
00:18:30,920 --> 00:18:34,520
 Dr. Wright has also been continuing to engage in the subject

288
00:18:34,520 --> 00:18:37,080
 as a biblical scholar and mythologist.

289
00:18:37,080 --> 00:18:40,720
 The difficulties for scholars who write

290
00:18:40,720 --> 00:18:43,280
 on the ethics of the Old Testament are manifold.

291
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:46,040
 Three dynamics are worth mentioning.

292
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:50,040
 The first is the challenge to relay the interrelated field

293
00:18:50,040 --> 00:18:53,200
 of study of law and ethics in the Old Testament.

294
00:18:53,200 --> 00:18:57,200
 Given that ethics is concerned about how people

295
00:18:57,200 --> 00:19:00,160
 should live with one another in a society,

296
00:19:00,160 --> 00:19:03,520
 it can hardly be denied that Old Testament ethics

297
00:19:03,520 --> 00:19:06,520
 is prominently fissure with collection of law,

298
00:19:06,520 --> 00:19:09,320
 which prescribe how people should act

299
00:19:09,320 --> 00:19:13,280
 with respect to others in certain circumstances.

300
00:19:13,280 --> 00:19:15,120
 In terms of social function,

301
00:19:15,120 --> 00:19:17,880
 Old Testament law appears to be tangible manifestation

302
00:19:17,880 --> 00:19:20,600
 of ethical principles that would engender

303
00:19:20,600 --> 00:19:23,320
 right interpersonal relationships in a social group.

304
00:19:23,320 --> 00:19:27,600
 But can Old Testament law as a whole simply be understood

305
00:19:27,600 --> 00:19:29,840
 to represent Old Testament ethics?

306
00:19:29,840 --> 00:19:31,640
 Apparently not.

307
00:19:31,640 --> 00:19:36,160
 While law prescribes for the most part external behavior,

308
00:19:36,160 --> 00:19:40,200
 ethics is commonly understood to be a moral vision

309
00:19:40,200 --> 00:19:42,320
 with more fundamental values

310
00:19:42,320 --> 00:19:45,560
 that regulate the lives of individuals as human beings.

311
00:19:45,560 --> 00:19:50,200
 Still, it is sometimes not as straightforward

312
00:19:50,200 --> 00:19:52,520
 when it comes to drawing ethical principles

313
00:19:52,520 --> 00:19:54,720
 from individual legal statements

314
00:19:54,720 --> 00:19:58,920
 or even legal terminology in the Old Testament.

315
00:19:58,920 --> 00:20:02,480
 One example is the Hebrew word mishpat,

316
00:20:02,480 --> 00:20:06,440
 which commonly translated as justice or judgment

317
00:20:06,440 --> 00:20:07,880
 in a legal sense,

318
00:20:07,880 --> 00:20:10,520
 might carry different ethical implications

319
00:20:10,520 --> 00:20:14,240
 that can only be assessed in particular context.

320
00:20:14,240 --> 00:20:17,600
 Even Dr. Wright defines mishpat in its broader sense

321
00:20:17,600 --> 00:20:20,200
 as a qualitative set of actions.

322
00:20:20,200 --> 00:20:22,920
 New answers in terms of ethical implications

323
00:20:22,920 --> 00:20:25,760
 might exist across its various usages

324
00:20:25,760 --> 00:20:27,120
 in the biblical tradition.

325
00:20:28,440 --> 00:20:30,760
 Despite the inherent challenge of relating law

326
00:20:30,760 --> 00:20:33,200
 and ethics in the Old Testament,

327
00:20:33,200 --> 00:20:35,840
 Dr. Wright's approach brings awareness

328
00:20:35,840 --> 00:20:37,720
 to the importance of envisioning

329
00:20:37,720 --> 00:20:40,040
 the relationship of law and ethics

330
00:20:40,040 --> 00:20:43,320
 in light of the narrative framework of the Old Testament.

331
00:20:43,320 --> 00:20:46,880
 In articulating Old Testament ethics,

332
00:20:46,880 --> 00:20:48,600
 Dr. Wright never looks at the laws

333
00:20:48,600 --> 00:20:50,480
 as revealed in the Torah per se,

334
00:20:50,480 --> 00:20:53,000
 but intends to understand them

335
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:55,440
 against the backdrop of Israel's origin

336
00:20:55,440 --> 00:20:57,960
 and her relationship with Yahweh.

337
00:20:57,960 --> 00:21:00,080
 Dr. Wright reminds us that

338
00:21:00,080 --> 00:21:02,360
 the ethical implication of Old Testament law

339
00:21:02,360 --> 00:21:04,720
 can only be fully grasped

340
00:21:04,720 --> 00:21:06,840
 in the context of Israel's narrative.

341
00:21:06,840 --> 00:21:11,440
 Set within the context of Israel's story with Yahweh,

342
00:21:11,440 --> 00:21:14,920
 Old Testament law is much more than a set of conduct

343
00:21:14,920 --> 00:21:17,520
 or rules demanded to humanity by God,

344
00:21:17,520 --> 00:21:21,600
 but it is revelatory of the defined purpose

345
00:21:21,600 --> 00:21:24,600
 in shaping the life of the community of God's people.

346
00:21:25,640 --> 00:21:28,320
 Dr. Wright's emphasis on the narrative nature

347
00:21:28,320 --> 00:21:29,840
 of the Old Testament

348
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:32,920
 not only bridges biblical law and ethics,

349
00:21:32,920 --> 00:21:34,920
 but also constitutes a basis

350
00:21:34,920 --> 00:21:39,000
 upon which law and ethics can be biblically related.

351
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:42,920
 The second challenge for scholars concerns the tensions

352
00:21:42,920 --> 00:21:46,080
 between the so-called diachronic historical approach

353
00:21:46,080 --> 00:21:48,120
 and the synchronic literary approach

354
00:21:48,120 --> 00:21:51,440
 in articulating a discourse on Old Testament ethics.

355
00:21:51,440 --> 00:21:54,920
 For historical critical scholars,

356
00:21:54,920 --> 00:21:56,360
 the ethical import of the Bible

357
00:21:56,360 --> 00:22:00,800
 lies in the real historical world behind the biblical text.

358
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:03,280
 Locating ethical truths in history,

359
00:22:03,280 --> 00:22:06,880
 they tend to look for real ethical values

360
00:22:06,880 --> 00:22:09,120
 that might have been held by ancient Israelites

361
00:22:09,120 --> 00:22:10,240
 in the biblical period.

362
00:22:10,240 --> 00:22:12,360
 Despite its contribution

363
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:15,600
 in uncovering the historical reality of the Bible,

364
00:22:15,600 --> 00:22:19,760
 the historical critical approach has its own limitations.

365
00:22:19,760 --> 00:22:21,600
 Not only does historical reconstruction

366
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:24,640
 remain in a large part a tentative project,

367
00:22:24,640 --> 00:22:28,400
 but excessive preoccupation with historical vicissitudes

368
00:22:28,400 --> 00:22:31,200
 would risk fragmentizing the biblical canon

369
00:22:31,200 --> 00:22:34,400
 rather than viewing it as a unified corpus

370
00:22:34,400 --> 00:22:37,120
 in terms of ethical insights.

371
00:22:37,120 --> 00:22:39,440
 John Barton, a known Old Testament scholar,

372
00:22:39,440 --> 00:22:43,480
 even advises against an Old Testament ethic at all,

373
00:22:43,480 --> 00:22:46,840
 as he sees no unity of ethical motives

374
00:22:46,840 --> 00:22:49,440
 across the various parts of the biblical tradition.

375
00:22:49,440 --> 00:22:52,280
 While historical critics attempt

376
00:22:52,280 --> 00:22:54,960
 to find ethical truths in history,

377
00:22:54,960 --> 00:22:57,920
 scholars who appreciate the Bible as literature

378
00:22:57,920 --> 00:23:02,400
 are inclined to adopt the synchronic literary approach

379
00:23:02,400 --> 00:23:05,000
 in extracting biblical ethics.

380
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:09,800
 For literary critics, it is story rather than history.

381
00:23:09,800 --> 00:23:13,120
 That should be the focus of investigation.

382
00:23:13,120 --> 00:23:15,200
 In other words, ethical principles

383
00:23:15,200 --> 00:23:18,000
 are found not in the world behind the biblical text,

384
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:20,400
 but are embedded in the world within the text.

385
00:23:22,320 --> 00:23:25,880
 Notwithstanding its appreciation of biblical accounts

386
00:23:25,880 --> 00:23:30,640
 as aesthetically crafted and ethically laden constructs,

387
00:23:30,640 --> 00:23:32,600
 the literary critical strategy

388
00:23:32,600 --> 00:23:35,080
 does not necessarily presuppose

389
00:23:35,080 --> 00:23:37,560
 a comprehensive Old Testament ethics

390
00:23:37,560 --> 00:23:40,440
 that undergirds all biblical texts.

391
00:23:40,440 --> 00:23:42,600
 Some literary critics rightly point us to the fact

392
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:45,200
 that there is a diverse material

393
00:23:45,200 --> 00:23:46,760
 in terms of ethical teachings

394
00:23:46,760 --> 00:23:48,680
 across the various biblical genres.

395
00:23:49,600 --> 00:23:52,600
 Yet, some might go too far in claiming

396
00:23:52,600 --> 00:23:55,120
 that the diversity is so great

397
00:23:55,120 --> 00:23:57,640
 that we can only formulate Old Testament ethics

398
00:23:57,640 --> 00:24:00,120
 according to a collection of books,

399
00:24:00,120 --> 00:24:03,480
 such as the Pentateuch, Historical Narratives,

400
00:24:03,480 --> 00:24:05,400
 Wisdom Literature, or Prophets.

401
00:24:05,400 --> 00:24:09,840
 So some might name it as Ethics in the Pentateuch,

402
00:24:09,840 --> 00:24:12,200
 Ethics in the Wisdom Literature,

403
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:14,840
 Ethics in the Prophets, and so forth.

404
00:24:14,840 --> 00:24:17,840
 While it might serve as a reminder for us

405
00:24:17,840 --> 00:24:20,080
 to incorporate a whole span of biblical books

406
00:24:20,080 --> 00:24:22,200
 in doing Old Testament ethics,

407
00:24:22,200 --> 00:24:23,880
 especially the lecture today

408
00:24:23,880 --> 00:24:26,680
 seems to be focused on the Pentateuch,

409
00:24:26,680 --> 00:24:28,160
 the literary critical strategy

410
00:24:28,160 --> 00:24:32,280
 might also risk disuniting biblical ethics

411
00:24:32,280 --> 00:24:36,480
 if no underpinning ethical tell-all is presumed.

412
00:24:36,480 --> 00:24:40,160
 In the face of this methodological dynama,

413
00:24:40,160 --> 00:24:42,760
 doctorized theological reading of the Old Testament

414
00:24:42,760 --> 00:24:47,000
 constitutes not only a possibility, but also a necessity.

415
00:24:47,960 --> 00:24:51,080
 For a comprehensive biblical ethics.

416
00:24:51,080 --> 00:24:54,320
 Indeed, the crucial issue concerning the dynama

417
00:24:54,320 --> 00:24:57,760
 lies not so much in the adopted reading strategy,

418
00:24:57,760 --> 00:25:00,600
 but in the very fact that the theological nature

419
00:25:00,600 --> 00:25:04,440
 of the Old Testament has not been prioritized.

420
00:25:04,440 --> 00:25:08,560
 Read in a Christian canonical perspective,

421
00:25:08,560 --> 00:25:10,640
 aspects of ethics in the Old Testament

422
00:25:10,640 --> 00:25:13,680
 is fundamentally theological.

423
00:25:13,680 --> 00:25:16,760
 As Dr. Wright asserts in his Old Testament Ethics,

424
00:25:16,760 --> 00:25:21,040
 ethical issues are at every point related to God,

425
00:25:21,040 --> 00:25:25,960
 to his character, his will, his actions, and his purpose.

426
00:25:25,960 --> 00:25:29,680
 Old Testament ethics is grounded ultimately

427
00:25:29,680 --> 00:25:32,680
 in the person of Yahweh, God of Israel,

428
00:25:32,680 --> 00:25:37,480
 who is also revealed as God of all creation and humanity.

429
00:25:37,480 --> 00:25:41,400
 Reflecting his quintessential character of justice,

430
00:25:41,400 --> 00:25:44,440
 righteousness, truth, and compassion,

431
00:25:44,440 --> 00:25:47,160
 Yahweh's moral demands and ethical expectations

432
00:25:47,160 --> 00:25:49,480
 are not only upon Israel,

433
00:25:49,480 --> 00:25:51,800
 but are also upon his people of all ages.

434
00:25:51,800 --> 00:25:54,840
 Within a theological covenantal framework

435
00:25:54,840 --> 00:25:56,840
 as prioritized by Dr. Wright,

436
00:25:56,840 --> 00:26:00,240
 Old Testament ethics is principally theocentric,

437
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:04,160
 which renders it canonical and comprehensive,

438
00:26:04,160 --> 00:26:06,680
 thereby saving it from being disunited,

439
00:26:06,680 --> 00:26:09,120
 as is sometimes the case in critical scholarship.

440
00:26:09,120 --> 00:26:11,760
 The third and last challenge I would like

441
00:26:11,760 --> 00:26:15,600
 to highlight today is, echoing with the lecture title

442
00:26:15,600 --> 00:26:18,320
 written for us, how we should apply

443
00:26:18,320 --> 00:26:20,440
 Old Testament ethics in our age,

444
00:26:20,440 --> 00:26:22,720
 and how far we can make it relevant

445
00:26:22,720 --> 00:26:24,880
 for the contemporary world.

446
00:26:24,880 --> 00:26:28,320
 In fact, a dynama concerning the applicability

447
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:31,400
 of Old Testament ethics has long been noted.

448
00:26:31,400 --> 00:26:34,120
 As Earl Davies succinctly points out,

449
00:26:34,120 --> 00:26:37,720
 on the one hand, many of the laws and customs of Bible

450
00:26:37,720 --> 00:26:39,400
 no longer seem relevant

451
00:26:39,400 --> 00:26:41,720
 to contemporary communities of faith.

452
00:26:41,720 --> 00:26:44,640
 On the other hand, many problems which do arise

453
00:26:44,640 --> 00:26:47,240
 in the complex technological world which we inhabit

454
00:26:47,240 --> 00:26:49,720
 are such that the Bible offers no exact guidance

455
00:26:49,720 --> 00:26:53,480
 or direction by which they can be resolved.

456
00:26:53,480 --> 00:26:57,000
 Thus, the dilemma of relevancy is too edged.

457
00:26:57,000 --> 00:26:58,960
 For those who start with the historical ethics

458
00:26:58,960 --> 00:27:02,240
 of the Old Testament would inevitably be confronted

459
00:27:02,240 --> 00:27:04,360
 with the historical cultural gap

460
00:27:04,360 --> 00:27:06,920
 between antiquity and our modern world.

461
00:27:06,920 --> 00:27:10,560
 While the challenge for the historical approach is evident,

462
00:27:10,560 --> 00:27:14,280
 any attempt that begins with modern ethical issues

463
00:27:14,280 --> 00:27:15,880
 is no easy way either.

464
00:27:15,880 --> 00:27:21,200
 In fact, a variety of ethics in a contemporary society,

465
00:27:21,200 --> 00:27:26,200
 for example, bioethics, medical ethics, political ethics,

466
00:27:26,200 --> 00:27:29,240
 social ethics, economic ethics, legal ethics,

467
00:27:29,240 --> 00:27:31,480
 family ethics, and so on,

468
00:27:31,480 --> 00:27:34,400
 adds to the complexity of modern ethics

469
00:27:34,400 --> 00:27:37,400
 and has the difficulties in applying biblical ethics

470
00:27:37,400 --> 00:27:41,880
 in our age. Notwithstanding the real and practical challenges,

471
00:27:41,880 --> 00:27:44,600
 we should not be deterred from seeking to relate

472
00:27:44,600 --> 00:27:47,440
 the Old Testament ethics to our contemporary life.

473
00:27:47,440 --> 00:27:50,680
 If we, as a community of faith,

474
00:27:50,680 --> 00:27:53,760
 are to believe what Dr. Wright envisions,

475
00:27:53,760 --> 00:27:56,080
 Israel is God's paradigm

476
00:27:56,080 --> 00:27:59,320
 of what a nation ought ideally to be,

477
00:27:59,320 --> 00:28:03,360
 and was therefore chosen to disclose God's wider purposes

478
00:28:03,360 --> 00:28:05,000
 to the rest of humanity,

479
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:08,000
 we are indeed sharing the same mission with Israel

480
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:10,920
 in propagating the ethical way of life

481
00:28:10,920 --> 00:28:13,280
 God demands of the whole humanity,

482
00:28:13,280 --> 00:28:15,280
 his very people on earth.

483
00:28:15,280 --> 00:28:18,440
 The relevance of Old Testament ethics,

484
00:28:18,440 --> 00:28:21,440
 therefore, finds its anchor in the conviction

485
00:28:21,440 --> 00:28:24,000
 that it is paradigmatic for all people

486
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:26,320
 across times and contexts.

487
00:28:26,320 --> 00:28:29,320
 With this belief held, the aforementioned dilemmas

488
00:28:29,320 --> 00:28:32,400
 might not necessarily dispirit us.

489
00:28:32,400 --> 00:28:36,800
 Rather, they come to remind us to be in a spirit of humility

490
00:28:36,800 --> 00:28:40,560
 as we seek to relate biblical ethical insights in our world.

491
00:28:40,560 --> 00:28:44,400
 Perhaps the theme of this lecture series written for us

492
00:28:44,400 --> 00:28:48,080
 means to speak to a humble heart and open ears

493
00:28:48,080 --> 00:28:50,760
 as we are eager to live out the scripture.

494
00:28:50,760 --> 00:28:54,240
 Lastly, I invite all of you to join me

495
00:28:54,240 --> 00:28:57,440
 in thanking Dr. Wright for his most insightful

496
00:28:57,440 --> 00:28:59,680
 and highly stimulating lecture.

497
00:28:59,680 --> 00:29:01,560
 Thank you very much, Dr. Wright. Thank you.

498
00:29:01,560 --> 00:29:04,720
 (audience applauding)

